=== Bibliographic and Authorial Context
- *Primary Author:* Dr. Anton Josef Kirchweger (c. 1695–Feb. 8, 1746), Councillor and Court Physicist of the Salzkammergut / Upper Austria. Identity established by marginal annotation of Dr. R.J.F. Schmidt (Hamburg, c. 1738–39): _"Doctor Kirchweger Stirus natione pro Autore Catenas Aureae Homeri se confessus est"_ — "Doctor Kirchweger from Steiermark, Austria, has identified himself as the author of the Golden Chain of Homer."
- *Corroborating Evidence:* Hermann Kopp (*Aurea Catena Homeri*, Braunschweig 1880) confirms Kirchweger's authorship from a Vienna manuscript catalogue (1786). Kirchweger's own work *Microscopium Basilii Valentini* (Berlin 1790) refers to "his" *Aurea Catena* over a dozen times; his third manuscript *Ars Senum seu Pandora Redux* confirms the same.
- *Three Titles:* (1) *Aurea Catena Homeri* (Golden Chain of Homer); (2) *Annulus Platonis* (Ring of Plato); (3) *Superius et Inferius Hermetis* (The Superior and Inferior of Hermes). The name "Homerus" is not from the Greek poet but from the Hermetic tradition — Homer's "golden chain" in the *Iliad* (VIII, 17–26) symbolises the chain interconnecting all of Nature.
- *The Rosenkreuzer Attribution:* The 1781 edition's preface (signed *Phlebochron*) names a "Herwerd von Forchenbrunn, medical teacher in Cromau, country physician in Moravia, a worthy member of our secret fraternity, name of Homerus." This is considered inexact or deliberately obscuring.
- *Editions:* 1723 (2 variants, Frankfurt & Leipzig, anon.); 1728; 1738 (Frankfurt & Leipzig; also Leipzig pocket ed. owned by Hof Rat Schmidt); 1754 (Jena); 1757 (Jena); 1759 (Vienna); 1762 (Latin, Dr. Ludovicus Favrat); 1763 (Latin); 1771 (*Annulus Platonis*, Berlin); 1781 (*Annulus Platonis*, Rosenkreuzer ed., Berlin & Leipzig). French adaptation: *La Nature Dévoilée*, Paris 1772 (2 vols). IGF Edition: 2025, transliterated from R.A.M.S. & original German editions by Justitius.
- *Third Part:* Not by Kirchweger. Explicitly excluded by the 1781 Rosenkreuzer editors as spurious. Its author (writing from Utrecht, October 18, 1654) is a separate philosopher. The IGF edition includes it for reference as Book III.
- *Primary Audience:* Prescribed as the "classical principal textbook" for disciples of the lower grades in the Rosicrucian order. Gerard Heym (*AMBIX* No. 1, 1937): "one of the most logical and readable books among a hundred books more or less absurdly speculative." An alchemical master, when asked which single book to save from a burning library, replied: "The Golden Chain of Homer. IF you can understand it."

=== The Ten Links of the Chain (from Heym / AMBIX, after the 1781 edition)
The frontispiece of the 1781 edition illustrates the chain with ten linked Latin descriptions:

+ *Chaos confusum* — The Undifferentiated Chaos.
+ *Spiritus Mundi volatilis incorporeus* — The volatile, incorporeal World Spirit.
+ *Spiritus Mundi acidus corporeus* — The acid, corporeal World Spirit (Nitrum / Acidum).
+ *Spiritus Mundi fixus alcalicus corporeus* — The fixed, alkaline, corporeal World Spirit (Salt / Alcali).
+ *Materia prima omnium concretorum sublunarium immediata seu Azoth* — The immediate First Matter of all sublunary concrete things / Azoth.
+ *Animalia* — Animals.
+ *Vegetabilia* — Vegetables / Plants.
+ *Mineralia* — Minerals.
+ *Spiritus Mundi concentratus fixus sive Extractum chaoticum purum* — The concentrated fixed World Spirit / pure Chaotic Extract.
+ *Perfectio consummata sive Quinta Essentia* — Consummated Perfection / Quintessence.

The *Art of Alchemy* is placed between Link 5 and the Reborn Chaos: the artist takes the immediate First Matter, resolves it back to Chaos via the Quinta Essentia, and the re-formation produces a perfected body — universal medicine for man and metals.

=== The Emerald Tablet (full text, as given by Phlebochron in the Foreword)
The work is explicitly framed as a commentary on the Tabula Smaragdina. The full text as reproduced:

#doctrine[
  "It is true and no lie, certain and truest of all, that that which is below is like that which is above, and that which is above is like that which is below, whereby the wonder-signs of a thing can be obtained. And just as all things are created by One alone, by the will of the Only One who thought of it before; so also, all things originate from the Only One Being, by appropriation. The sun is its father, the moon its mother, the wind has carried it in its belly. Its nurse is the earth. This is the father of all perfection in the whole world. His power is total when he is transformed into earth. You must separate the earth from the fire, the fire from the crude, gently, with great understanding. He ascends from the earth up to heaven, and descends again from heaven to the earth, and receives the power of the upper and the lower. When you have achieved this, you will possess the splendour of the whole world, and all darkness will fly from you. This is the strongest strength of all strength, for it overcomes all subtle and volatile things, and penetrates that which is crude. Thus, the world is created. And by means of this one thing the most wonderful works are accomplished. That is why I have been called: The Thrice-Great Hermes, because I possess three parts of the truth. Everything I have said about the work of the sun has been fulfilled."
]

=== The Double Abyss — Poem of the *Abyssi Duplicatae* (1781 ed., trans. Nintzel)
#doctrine[
  One abyss calls forth another. Together they form a hard bouquet. / The volatile must become quite fixed; Steam and water must turn into earth. / Heaven itself must be earthly, Or else no life will enter the earth. / The highest must become the lowest; The Lowest again the Highest. / The fixed must become quite volatile; Water and steam must be the earth. / The Earth must fly high up to Heaven; Heaven must creep into the centre of the Earth. / Thus, Heaven and Earth must become reversed, If the lowest is to become the highest. / The volatile Dragon kills the fixed; The fixed forces the volatile into Death. / Thus must stand revealed — the quintessence and what it can do.
]

=== Chapter I: What Nature Is
*Definition:* Nature is the amalgamation — both visible and invisible worlds — functioning solely through the essence and presence of God. The *active* part is the universal World Spirit (*Spiritus Mundi*, *Anima Mundi*); the *passive* part is the "immutably working law of motion" impressed on all creatures at creation.

*The Two Principles:*
- *Agens (Active):* The World Spirit — one and the same in all created things. Called: Spiritus Mundi, Anima Mundi, Archeus, Mercurius Vitae, living water, the true FIAT. It is universal but acts differently in each creature according to that creature's inner structure.
- *Patiens (Passive):* The created body with its specific, inborn "law of motion" — the inner structure through which the Agens works.

*The Mill Analogy:* Paper mills, flour mills, stamp mills — all driven by one energy source (water) yet each producing a different result according to its inner construction. *Water = universal Spiritus Mundi. Inner structure = the law of motion specific to each creature.*

#hm-note[
  Corrollary III, Chapter I — the primary Tyro objective: "Whoever perfectly understands this active Spirit and the above-mentioned law of motion in all types of creatures in relation to the differences proper to them, will also recognise the Lawgiver in His infinite wisdom... He will possess natural science perfectly and is on the highest level of Hermetic philosophy." This is the entire goal of Year 1.
]

*Corrollaries:*
- *I:* All Nature consists of two basic origins: the doer (spiritual) and the moved (corporeal). Fire acts on Air; Air acts on Water; Water acts on Earth; everything is originally made effective by the World Spirit.
- *II:* All practical investigation of Nature undertaken without correct knowledge of the World Spirit and the laws of the subject is "foolish and fruitless."
- *III:* The student must choose *one thing only* as the object of initial study — investigate it completely — and then proceed to the next. "For the whole of Nature resembles a circular chain, the links of which hang exactly together. When an enlightened spiritual man has finally come to perfectly know the first link, it will be easy for him to expand his knowledge from this to the second, from that to the third, and so on... *one book opens and explains another.*"

=== Chapter II: Out of Whom / Out of What Everything Was Born
*The FIAT:* God emitted from His mouth the holy Word of Power: FIAT! — which became an immeasurable vapour, fog, mist, smoke. This smoke condensed into the *Chaotic Water* — the first matter of all things.

*Water and Spirit as the Primal Two-in-One:*
- Water = visible, corporeal = *Patiens*. The subject, the body, the casing, the instrument.
- Spirit = invisible, incorporeal = *Agens*. The active agent, the World Spirit, the blacksmith of all natural things (*Sperma universi*).
- "Water without the spirit is without power; spirit without water is without duration, because spirit must have a body if it is to affect corporeal things."

*The Great Void:* The pre-creation void is not literal emptiness but *pure potentiality*. Like an ink-pot: it contains no letters in actuality, but a skilled hand can form all letters from it. The Corollary: "Everything, therefore, has originated in ONE. Out of which a thing becomes, into the same it can also be changed back. Therefore everything can be changed back into that ONE — into a fiery active water."

*The Luciferian Cosmogony (Lecture by an Elder Brother):* When Lucifer closed off the influx of the Divine Light-Waters and began to act according to his own will, the Almighty withdrew the irradiation, arousing a mighty fire. This fire drove tremendous vapours throughout Lucifer's realm, which condensed into the *Chaotic Water* — filled with an active spirit — from which all planetary creation arose in the six Days of Creation. "These waters... were filled with an active spirit throughout their expansion, whereby the Almighty Word of creation brought forth all the creatures of our planetary world."

=== Chapter III: How Everything Was Born
*The Primordial Process:* The two-fold Chaotic Water was warmed and heated by the implanted Spirit; it began to ferment, blister, and putrefy. In the beginning it was bright and clear. Through putrefaction it became turbid and divided into: a spiritual-subtle part; a half-spiritual/half-physical part; and a totally physical part.

*The Five States of Prime Matter — the Unfolding of the One:*
+ *One:* Simple, undivided Water.
+ *Two:* Water + hidden Spirit (two in one).
+ *Three:* Volatile + Acidum + Alcali — or: Spiritus + Anima + Corpus — or: Heaven + Air + (Water + Earth combined).
+ *Four:* The Four Elements — Fire/Heaven, Air, Water, Earth.
+ *Five:* The Fifth Essence — the perfect, indestructible Being beyond the four destructible elements.

*The Order of Separation by Degrees:* By the rule of degrees (*positivum, comparativum, superlativum*) the subtlest rises first: Heaven (finest, most active, full of life) → Air (sky) → Water → Earth (most fixed, coarsest). "God separated one subtle thing after another leaving the coarsest, each according to its particular order and law."

*The Universal Seed Command:* God saw that the separated Chaos could never coalesce back into One without destroying all creation. Therefore He commanded the four elements to produce a *universal seed* — a *Sperma Universi* — which would recombine the four into one and serve as the vehicle of birth, preservation, destruction, and rebirth of all things. This seed is the perpetually regenerated Chaotic Water — dew, rain, snow, hail, frost.

Three orders of seed were commanded: (1) *Universal* — the Spiritus Mundi; (2) *Elemental* — the seed of each separate element; (3) *Particular* — the seed of each individual creature in each of the three kingdoms.

=== Chapter IV: In What Manner the Universal Seed Was Begotten
*The Fourfold Marriage:*
- Father / Husband / Agens: Heaven (Fire) and Air.
- Mother / Wife / Patiens: Water and Earth.

#doctrine[
  *The Rule of Intermediaries* — "Non transiri posse ab uno extremo ad alterum extremum absque medio." One cannot pass from one extreme to another without an intermediary. "Every artist should take careful note of this. For countless thousands make mistakes and fail solely because they do not consider this point."
]

*The Descent (Fixation):* Heaven → Air → Water → Earth. Each step requires the *next-subtler* to be united with the *next-coarser*: Heaven with Air first (both subtle); then Air with Water (both intermediate); then Water with Earth (both condensed). *Heaven can never become Earth directly.* "As soon as they meet, the union can occur instantaneously — but one must go step by step."

*The Ascent (Volatilisation):* Earth → Water → Air → Heaven. Earth is turned with Water; Water is dissolved with Air; Air is thinned with Heaven. This reversal is equally mandatory.

*Degrees Within Degrees:* Each element itself contains inner degrees. The subtlest portion of Earth must first meet the thickest Water; the subtlest Water the thickest Air, etc. "Nature has mixed the thick Earth with the thin; she does not throw the differing degrees together, but one subtle thing in turn after another."

#lab[
  *Practical Demonstration of Intermediary Degrees (Ch. IV):*
  Take field earth. Add water, stir, let settle. The coarse earth sinks; the dissolved salt (virgin earth) rises and unites with the water. This "virgin earth" is the natural intermediary. To go further: distil the virgin-earth water into a "spiritual water." Only then does it regain the power to separate the next finer earth from the remaining gross mass. Each step must find the appropriate *intermediary*. This is the model for every laboratory separation.
]

=== Chapter V: The Spiritus Mundi — The Reborn Chaotic Water
*How the Seed is Forged:* Heaven perspires invisibly due to its ceaseless motion-generated heat. These vapours descend into Air. Air (the first intermediary) catches and coagulates them. Then the lower vapours of Water and Earth rise upward. In the medium of the Air, all four efluences meet, co-mingle, and produce the *universal seed* — the *Spiritus Mundi*. This is the perpetually reborn Chaotic Water. "This offspring of the four elements is the aforesaid general procreator of all things, the incomprehensible Nature Spirit controlling all things."

*The Fifth Element:* The Spiritus Mundi, when it cannot mingle with the destructible elements (due to its purity), soars above them as the *quintum elementum* — an ethereal, indestructible Spirit. *"Quintum Elementum est Spiritus aethereus incorruptibilis."*

*The Descent into Bodies:* The Spiritus Mundi descends through sidereal effluences into the subtlest fire-evaporations, then into air-evaporations, then through meteors (rain, dew, hail) into bodies — animal, vegetable, mineral. It even descends to the Earth's centre where, with the help of the central fire, it forms metals in subterranean workshops.

*The Hermaphroditic Mercury Axiom:* "Mercury (that is, of the philosophers) can be found in all things, and none of them can be found under the solar circle in which this divine sub-architect does not lie hidden in the more or less firm fetters of coagulation." — *Nihil sub sole existit, in quo non reperiatur argentum vivum Hermaphroditus noster adamicus.* The Art consists in setting him free from these fetters.

=== Chapter VI: Of Heaven and Its Influences
*Heaven as Father:* The *primum agens*, the first worker, the male seed, the soul and life of all things. A very fine steam — light, pure, volatile, full of life. Kirchweger distinguishes: the Empyrean of God (unchanged, inviolable) vs. the *elemental heaven* (fire) which does change and interact.

*The Effluence Cycle:* Heaven perspires upward (cannot go higher than itself, by divine command); therefore it descends into Air. Air catches it, coagulates it, and eventually it condenses into rain, falling to Earth. This is the cosmic clockwork: one wheel drives another — Heaven drives Air, Air drives Water, Water drives Earth.

*The Archaeus:* The inner life-principle of each creature — the Archeus (from Greek "I Begin") — is the same World Spirit under another name: *the beginning and origin of the life of all creatures.* In Man it rules all physiological functions; in metals it rules the ripening process.

*Self-Replenishment:* Heaven does not diminish by giving out its effluences. The vapours that rise from below, refined by their long ascent through all degrees of Air, return to Heaven and replenish it. *"Corruptio unius est generatio alterius."* The quantities of the four elements remain constant (in the same number, weight, and measure as originally divided from Chaos) until the final fire described in II Peter III.

=== Chapter VII: Of the Air and Its Influence
*Air as First Intermediary:* "Air is a first intermediate for uniting Heaven with Water and Earth, without which Heaven could not become reconciled with water and earth." Air catches the total heavenly influence, then converts the lower watery and earthly vapours into company with it, forging the beginning of the universal seed.

*Maria Prophetissa:* "One vapour or steam attracts or coagulates another (of a similar nature)." This is the axiom of like-attracting-like in the vapour state — foundational for understanding all condensation and cohobation.

#doctrine[
  "Earth is a fixed Heaven; Heaven is a volatile Earth; Air is a rarefied Water; Water is a condensed Air. One is not different from another except that one is volatile and the other fixed, one liquid or dissolved, the other thick or coagulated... when the volatile is made fixed, the fixed made volatile, the coagulated dissolved and the dissolved coagulated, one is changed into another and is yet what it had been before — the first primordial matter of things."
  — Chapter VII: the complete *Aurea Catena* doctrine in one paragraph
]

=== Chapter VIII: Of Water and Its Influence
*Water as Mother and Second Intermediary:* The first *Patiens*, female seed, the menstruum of the great world. "Water is a coagulated Heaven, a thickened Air, a liquid Earth — a steam changed into water." Together with Earth, the mother of all things.

*For the Artist:* If one intermediary is insufficient to unite two substances, use two. If two fail, use three — *but always of the same kingdom*. "Creatures from the subterranean kingdom agree together; things from the vegetable kingdom combine easily with others from the same realm." *"Simile gaudet simili"* — like rejoices in its like.

*Why Water is Essential:* "Spirit must have a body if it is to affect corporeal things. God intended it to be so that spirit should affect everything in all creatures by means of water, because water mixes easily with all things and through it spirit can soften, penetrate, give birth, and also destroy everything again."

=== Chapter IX: Of the Earth and Its Influence
*Earth as Receptacle:* The nethermost, most fixed, most coagulated element. Earth is the centre and vessel of all heavenly influences. Its inherent property is *cold* — the contracting, binding principle. "The earth is the noblest seat of that womb which attracts and receives the seed from the male part of the world."

*The Volatile Earth / Salt Astrale:* Not all earth is dense stone. There exists a *volatile earth* — the *Sal Astrale* (astral salt) — which floats above our heads and is incorporated into all creatures at creation. This is the *virgin earth* (*Aphar-Min-Ha-Adamah* of Scripture): it reaches us first in dew, rain, snow, hail, and shooting stars. Dr. Giese (physician in Cologne) collected rainwater, evaporated it on a porcelain plate in a sealed room, and obtained a red earth resembling kermes antimony (Cinnabar) — a few grains of which effected great cures.

*All Four Elements Mutually Immanent:* "In water there is earth; in the Earth there is water. In Air there is Heaven and Heaven in Air. Heaven, Air, Water and Earth are forever together and in each other, and none is without having the other in all its parts." A mote of earth contains Heaven and Air — proven by the fact that a dried root or precious stone, though cut from its living matrix, retains its virtues and conveys health or disease to the wearer through its imperceptible evaporation.

*Motion and Warmth:* Every motion, however imperceptible, generates warmth. The earth, through its inherent motion (and the central fire), continuously steams. These vapours join those from water and air in the atmosphere to regenerate the Spiritus Mundi.

=== Chapter X: Discovery of the True Universal Seed — the Gur
*Theoretical Proof:* The universal seed (dew, rain, snow, hail, frost) must: (a) contain all four elements, (b) be capable of generating animal, vegetable, and mineral creatures. The following series of procedures proves this.

*Step 1 — The Putrefied Rainwater:* Collect rainwater (thunderstorm rain is best) in a clean barrel. Filter through felt. Place in a lukewarm, covered location away from direct sun, wind, and rain. Allow to stand *one month without stirring*. Observe: the previously clear, crystalline water becomes turbid; a brown, spongy, greasy, slippery earth separates and eventually sinks to the bottom. *This earth is the true universal fossil dust — the Gur.* Heaven and Air remain invisible in the water; Water and Earth have become manifest through putrefaction.

*Step 2 — The Crystallisation Experiment (Identifying the Gur as Nitre and Salt):* Boil the putrefied water down to one-third. Let it cool to lukewarm. Filter. Place in a cool cellar in a tin basin, glass dish, or wooden pot. During the night, the World Spirit will appear in two visible forms:
- *Upper form:* Transparent, diamond-shaped crystalline matter adhering to the sides of the vessel and to any wood placed in it. Cast this on burning coals: it immediately declares its name — *NITRE* (saltpetre). The universal acid / male seed.
- *Lower form:* A somewhat brownish, heavier mass that sinks to the bottom. Cast this on coals: it cracks and crackles. Its name is *SALT* (common salt / alkaline salt). The universal alkali / female seed.

N.B.: "Nitre, sublimated from rainwater, is not different from common saltpetre in its effects. The salt cracks and crackles like common salt. Both are fully confirmed by this test as the seed of the whole macrocosm."

*Step 3 — Generation of the Three Kingdoms from Rainwater Elements:*
- *Mineral generation:* Take the earth fraction (dried, powdered). Moisten repeatedly with the second distillate (Water fraction) — not with Heaven and Air. Dry in the sun repeatedly. The earth becomes heavy and sandy — it has acquired a mineral nature. Assay reveals traces of silver and gold.
- *Vegetable generation:* Take the same earth. Moisten with two parts Water + one part Heaven & Air. Set in the air (not direct sun). Various small plants grow. Sow ordinary seed into it and the seed fruit also grows from it.
- *Animal generation:* Take the same earth. Add one part Water + two to three parts Heaven & Air (consistency of thin honey). Set in lukewarm air and mild sunlight. Within a few days, various small animals appear and multiply.

#hm-note[
  *The practical significance:* This experiment proves that dew and rain are the universal seed — capable of generating the creatures of all three kingdoms depending only on the ratio of fixed (Earth+Water) to volatile (Heaven+Air) components. The mineral kingdom requires more of the fixed; the animal kingdom requires more of the volatile; the vegetable stands in the middle.
]

=== Chapters XI–XV: Nitre and Salt are the Universal Seed (The Proof by Distribution)
A systematic proof that Nitre (the universal acid, the male seed, Heaven and Air) and Salt (the universal alkali, the female seed, Water and Earth) are found in every realm of Nature and are the sole generative and destructive principle.

*Chapter XI — In Air:* Lightning, thunder, hail, and explosions are all the meeting of volatile Nitre (descending from Heaven) with volatile Alkali (ascending from Earth as vapour) in a dry, heated state. *Experiment:* Melt saltpetre in a crucible; add Sal Ammoniac, coal dust, sulphur, or volatile oils → immediate fulmination. Add a fixed alkali (Sal Tartari, chalk, lime) → no explosion, only friendly union. This demonstrates: volatile Nitre + volatile Alkali = explosive; volatile Nitre + fixed Alkali = peaceful fixation.

*The Aurum Fulminans Analysis (Ch. XI):* Gold dissolved in Aqua Regia and precipitated with Oleum Tartari (potassium carbonate solution) produces fulminating gold. The cause is not the gold's sulphur (as most believe) but the highly volatile Nitre from Aquafort (saltpetre + vitriol) and the volatile Sal Ammoniac retained in the gold. Proof: (a) wetting the gold prevents fulmination; (b) boiling with fixed alkali removes the fulmination permanently; (c) precipitating with volatile alkali instead of fixed makes it fulminate three times more violently than with Oleum Tartari. "The cause of the Fulmen is the volatile saltpetre and Sal Ammoniac — not the sulphur of gold."

*Chapter XII — In Water and Earth:* Every kind of earth (field, meadow, bog, mountain, valley, red clay, limestone) — dissolve in water, filter, evaporate to one-third, let crystallise → saltpetre and salt always result. Every river carries dissolved saltpetre and salt into the sea; the sea's salt-predominance over saltpetre is because the constant motion of the sea (waves, wind) reverberates the saltpetre and converts it into fixed Alkali / salt.

*Chapter XIII — In Animals:* Animals consist of volatile salt (their stink in putrefaction), fixed salt (ash after calcination), and inflammable oiliness (their sulphurous-nitrous nature). "That the animal kingdom is very saltpetric is shown by the saltpetre-makers who dig up the living and bedrooms of farmers where their children urinate incessantly — that seeps into the soil and is transformed into excellent saltpetre." Cemetery earth from decomposed bodies, when lixiviated, yields both Nitre and Salt.

*Chapter XIV — In Plants:* Plants grow from nitrous-salty rain, dew, and earth. Their burning spirit (Spiritus Vini / alcohol) is volatile Nitre; their oil is liquid Nitre; their ash is Alcali. *Experiment:* Melt two parts salt + one part saltpetre together in a crucible; dissolve in ten parts rainwater; soak a seed in this, dry it, and sow alongside an unsoaked seed in the same soil. The soaked seed will show measurably faster growth, finer fruit, and greater vigour — directly proportional to the Nitre and Salt supplied.

*Chapter XV — In Minerals:* The subterranean generation of minerals follows the same Nitre-Salt principle. The complete sequence from Gur to Metal:
+ Corrosive salty vapours (spiritual Nitre + Salt dissolved by the central fire) rise through the crevices of mountains.
+ They adhere to rock walls, condense into corrosive water, and attack the earth.
+ The earth swells, becomes greasy and sticky → *Gur* (the distant first matter of metals — not yet metallic).
+ The Gur is continuously attacked by more rising vapours → becomes increasingly sulphurous → *Sulphur*.
+ The Sulphur, further digested by central heat, loses combustibility → becomes *Arsenic*.
+ The Arsenic is ripened by continued moderate heat → *Marcasite* (the nearest matter to metals).
+ The Marcasite is fixed and congealed by strong, even central heat → *Metal*.
+ Gold (☉) and Silver (☽) result from *moderate, even digestion over long periods with the most subtle and pure earth*.
+ Base metals (♄, ♃, ♀, ♂) result from *grosser earth, uneven digestion, or excess of corrosive*.

N.B.: "Vitriol or aluminous earth (Gur) is the root; Sulphur and Arsenic are the stem; Marcasite is the flower or blossom; Metals are the seed — the completed birth and offspring." Every marcasite, when assayed, gives off a fixed grain of perfect or imperfect metal.

=== Chapter XVI: Putrefaction — The Major Gate and Key to Nature
*The Doctrine:* Without putrefaction (prior maceration, digestion, or fermentation — whether quick or slow), no true dismemberment can be accomplished in universals, specifics, or individuals. Putrefaction is "the KEY to all dissolution and separation" (Basilius Valentinus).

*What Putrefaction Does:* The implanted Spirit, through its ceaseless motion, generates warmth; warmth opens the pores of every body; the Spirit penetrates; the volatile parts begin to steam; the body softens, separates, dissolves. "Putrefaction is that wonderful blacksmith who turns Earth into Water, Water into Air, Air into Fire; and again turns Fire into Air, this into Water, and Water into Earth — ceaselessly, without stopping even one minute."

*The Rate of Putrefaction:* Animals putrefy fastest (great excess of volatile spirit + volatile salt → intolerable stench). Vegetables putrefy readily (excess moisture). Minerals putrefy slowest (fixed, dense, little moisture). Water animals putrefy faster than land animals. The artist who cannot get a mineral subject into putrefaction should resort first to the animal kingdom's principles to "open" it.

=== Chapter XVII: What Putrefaction Really Is
*The Spirit as the Cause:* Putrefaction is not caused by cold but by the warmth arising from the ceaseless motion of the implanted Spirit. "Cold extinguishes life; warmth causes putrefaction." Evidence: iron reddened by hammering on a cold anvil; stones heated by rubbing; two sticks kindled by friction — all warmth arises from motion.

*The Two Principles Personified:* The Spirit (Nitre) is characterized as a being "full of fire — white, ice-cold, crystalline, transparent in appearance, yet so fiery within that if heated in the Earth's centre it would blow up the whole world" — but when it meets its *"brother or cold wife"* (the Salt, the Venus of Nature), it is tamed: "She embraces him and grabs his middle, so that he should cool and extinguish his anger in love... as soon as he is embraced by his Venus and enchained in bonds of love, he not only does not harm his enemies but attracts them to his love, socialises with them, and forms an eternal alliance with them."

*The Five Names of the One Spirit:* According to its state, the one universal Spirit receives different names:
- *Volatile / Steam:* Heaven, Air, Volatile, Agens, male seed, Anima.
- *Half-fixed / Corporeal:* Water, Acidum, Spiritus, Sulphur, Nitre.
- *Fixed:* Earth, Fixum, Patiens, Alcali, woman, magnet, Corpus, Salt.
"This is the whole knowledge of all things, for in whatever form and shape we meet something, we give it a name to distinguish it from other objects."

=== Chapter XVIII: Results of Putrefaction
In putrefaction, the Volatile turns into the Acidum; the Acidum into the Alcali; the Alcali (under other conditions) back into the Acidum; the Acidum back into the Volatile. The separation is visible:
- Before putrefaction: rainwater is entirely volatile and clear, distilling completely.
- After one month's putrefaction: it divides into (1) the Volatile water (the "etheric mercurial Spirit" — small droplets, rising quickly, no wateriness in the head); (2) the Acidum / Nitre; (3) the alkaline salt; (4) the faeces (fixed earth remnant).

*The Smell as the Sign:* The smell of putrefaction is caused by the volatile parts being warmed and driven through the pores — the most volatile salt stinks worst. Coal / Caput Mortuum (C.M.) has almost no smell. "Old wines, the longer they lie in cold cellars, the more fragrant they become; the Spiritus Vini goes over first in distillation and surpasses all subsequent parts in smell."

=== Chapter XIX: How Volatile → Acid → Alkali (and the Reverse)
*The Acidum as Hermaphroditic Janus / Copulator:* "The Acidum is the medium and intermediary, the Sequester, Copulator, and Uniter of all things — because it is neither too volatile nor too fixed, but in the middle. It is the true chymical Janus who looks with one eye at the Volatile but with the other at the Alkali. When he gets the Volatile, he unites inseparably; if he gets the Alkali, he also joins inseparably. When all three get together, the union is so great that rather than separating, all three stay steadfast in the fire, or gradually vaporise all three at the same time."

*The Mechanism:* As the Spirit heats and ferments in water, it becomes sharp → this is the Acidum forming. The Acidum dissolves more earth → the earth alkalises the Acidum. The Acidum attracts the Volatile to sustain itself → both become increasingly fixed. If Alkali exceeds: everything becomes fixed (stone). If Volatile exceeds: everything becomes volatile (vapour). The Acidum stands in the middle as mediator and can swing either way depending on proportions.

*The Famous Error of Alchemists:* Spiritus Vini (most volatile) cannot be united directly with Sal Tartari (most fixed Alkali). "Ab uno extremo ad alterum non datur transitus." The cause of failure: no intermediary. The fix: add wine vinegar (Acetum) first. The vinegar is the Acidum = the natural intermediary between Spiritus Vini and Sal Tartari. "Add Acetum rectificatum to Spiritus Vini rectificato — they unite immediately, without resistance. Add an Alkali — it dissolves and unites. Provided all three are in their right ratio and weight, you will separate nothing thereafter but insipid Phlegma, because the Spiritus Vini has congealed upon the Alkali through the vinegar inseparably."

