=== Practical Tyro Applications (Year 1)
- *Collection of Thunderstorm Rain:* Collect during or immediately after a lightning storm (highest Nitre concentration); filter through felt; store in clean glass. This is the most charged form of the Universal Seed.
- *Collection of May Dew:* Before sunrise in spring, when the atmospheric Spiritus Mundi is most concentrated and solar radiation has not yet re-volatilised it. Wipe from plant leaves and grass with clean cloths; wring into glass vessels.
- *The Gur Experiment (Ch. X):* Collect rainwater → stand covered, lukewarm, one month → observe separation of volatile (clear upper water) from earthy Gur (brown, spongy bottom) → identification of Nitre and Salt by fire test.
- *Generation from Rainwater Elements (Ch. X):* Use the three fractions (Heaven + Air = first distillate; Water = second distillate; Earth = dried residue) to generate mineral sand, vegetable growth, and small animals as described in Chapter X. This is a *proof of competence* — demonstrating that the student understands the three kingdoms as products of differing ratios of fixed to volatile.
- *The Vinegar-Spirit-Alkali Union (Ch. XIX):* Perform the practical demonstration of Chapter XIX with Spiritus Vini, rectified vinegar, and Sal Tartari to *experience in the hands* the law of intermediaries. This should be performed both in the correct order (with vinegar as intermediary) and in the incorrect order (Spiritus Vini + Sal Tartari directly) to feel the difference.
- *Three-Kingdom Vinegar Study:* Prepare and compare: plant vinegar (Acetum wine), mineral acid (dilute Spirit of Nitre or Vitriol), and universal acid (from putrefied dew water). Observe the difference in their action on chalk (fixed Earth) and their willingness to unite with Spiritus Vini with and without intermediaries.
- *Observation of Mineral Vapour in a Cave or Mine (if accessible):* Observe the condensation of corrosive vapours on rock walls; the formation of white crystalline mineral efflorescences (often vitriol or alum); the presence of Gur in crevices near coal seams. This is the direct macrocosmic equivalent of the laboratory's artificial dismemberment.

=== Front Matter: To The Reader (R.A.M.S. / HWN Introduction)
The IGF edition preserves the original R.A.M.S. introduction by Hans W. Nintzel (HWN). Key content:

"With the production of the present work, R.A.M.S. (Restorers of Alchemical Manuscripts Society), may have accomplished their Magnum Opus." Eight people contributed across more than two years: Leone Muller (translation of ~600 pages of archaic German), Kevin Masman and Daniel Dullies (alchemical accuracy editing), Judy Hipskind and Mary Roberts (final typing), Jody Nintzel (illustration), David Ham (symbols and proofreading), Hans Nintzel (final production and editing).

The "one book to save" story: An R.A.M.S. producer asked a recognised alchemical master: "If your house was on fire and you could save only ONE book from your library, which one would you save?" The teacher replied: "Well, it would be the Golden Chain of Homer." Pressed: "Is this THE most important book of alchemy?" The teacher looked away, then answered: *"Yes. IF you can understand it!!"*

Gerhard Dorn's warning, cited in the introduction: *"The theory is dry without the praxis. Doing the laboratory work will thoroughly ingrain the theory and make it LIVE within and without you."*

=== Front Matter: Preface (German edition, referencing Goethe)
The original preface to the German edition establishes the work's standing in 19th-century intellectual life:

"The *Aurea Catena Homeri* was a famous book; today it is forgotten and buried under the dust of hundreds of years in our libraries. In the past, however, an uncountable number of people have read and studied it; even the best of that time, like *Goethe*, gained an array of inspiring thoughts from the *Annulus Platonis*." Goethe's own words (quoted in the preface): *"From the sky it comes, to the sky it rises, and down again to earth it must come, eternally changing."* This was, according to Goethe himself, *the idea he liked best* in the *Aurea Catena*: the interconnection of all creation in a secret circulation.

The preface ends with: *"Aperta jam porta, intra in conclave, amice!"* — "The door is already open; go into the room, my friend!" — which became the R.A.M.S. motto for the edition.

=== Front Matter: Introduction (Edition History with Schmidt Note and Phlebochron)
The original Introduction (p.10–16) provides the editorial history. Key points not captured elsewhere:
- Schmidt was "born in 1702 in Celle, died in 1761 in Copenhagen; Dr. med., general practitioner and alchemist in Hamburg, and Hof Rat of Darmstadt/Hessen." He bequeathed his entire library to Hamburg Library. His *Enchiridion Alchymico-Physicum* (Jena, 1739) was influenced by the *Aurea Catena*.
- The marginal annotation in Latin: *"Doctor Kirchweger Stirus natione pro Autore Catenas Aureae Homeri se confessus est."*
- The 1781 Rosicrucian editors were identified as Johann Gottfried Jugel (1707–1786) and Johann Christoph Wöllner (1732–1800).
- The edition was widely used in the Hamburg-Rosenkreuz circle.
- The COMMENTS section (p.15–16) provides the Agrippa/Pythagoras synthesis: *"In nature there exists a certain connection and common characteristic in occult forces. These cause a superior force to shoot out its rays through its inferior magnets in a continuous cycle, extending to the lowest of creatures. And vice versa, the inferior can rise to the uppermost through an ascending scale. That is why he is a true Magus who uses the things that lie manifest before one's eyes as if they were so many magnets intended for the attraction of the occult forces."* — Agrippa, *De Philosophia Occulta*, I.37–39.

=== Front Matter: Explanation of the Annuli Platonis — The Chain Poem with Footnotes
The full poem from the 1781 frontispiece, with the critical symbolic footnotes by the Rosicrucian editors:

*The poem:* "The Chain of Homer is proved thus: After the chaos pulls asunder, a volatile spirit must forge it. *Spiritus Mundi* is its name. Frost, dew, snow, rain and everything from above are betrothed to it in faithful company. Here is contained the volatile seed of the world from the upper realms, when it falls into the lower. From that it takes on a body when it glows visibly before our eyes. *Nitrum* is known to the whole world — who is there to tell all his power? It is he that can forge many a thing. To him the lower realm is subject; neither can the upper dispense with him. He must give birth to the whole of nature... He is the father of all things, who can conquer the fortresses of the world. His power has been given him by the Creator. His realm is over heaven, earth and the sea. *Adam* he is in all things; out of him *Eve* must also spring. Then the goal will be reached when the whole earth becomes fertile, when he becomes fixed and no longer flashes, and Eve sits next to him. Sun, moon, the sea, and the earth turn him to Eve through constant motion — through heat and cold, through constant movement of the sea, with Adam rises Eve, who is called common Salt and Alkali, who feeds the children of the whole world with her blood. For when man and woman get together, a perfect fruit will be forged from them..."

"This is proved by the volatile realm of the animals. Not volatile, not fixed — note well. The *Vegetable Hermaphrodite* also shows of what it is forged. The fixed ores and stones give evidence that they are proper to Nitre and Salt. Fire and Air, Water and Earth, desire of it the active part. When now the noble world-seed has been made fixed — steam and water have also been brought to earth — then is made, and also accomplished, that which all the world esteems most highly. Fixed must the volatile become; out of water and steam turn to earth. *And when it becomes a red dry blood, it is the world's treasure and highest good. A perfect perfection, which drives away all poverty and disease.*"

*Footnote 6 (on the hidden symbol):* "The symbol comprises a great secret, of which nothing can be said at present."

*Footnote 7 (on ☉ as World Soul):* "The symbol of ☉ is here given because the World Soul, or the philosophical ☉, being the foreman of God who forges all things above and below, therefore also produces the meteors, has his seat chiefly in the sun, into which he was drawn and locked by Divine omnipotence on the fourth day of creation."

*Footnote 8 (on Welling's definition of Nitre):* "Its sphere consists of the whole world; it has the ray of the upper light and the lower. Consequently, it consists of volatile and alkaline fixed parts, and is a wonder salt of nature." — Welling, Part I, Ch. 3, Sec. 19.

*Footnote 9 and 10 (on the Philosophical Vitriol):* "Here we see the character of the Philosophical Vitriol, from which the double Mercurius is prepared, through which all things are transformed into the pure tinctural nature. Consequently, it gives indeed fat and good soups!" — The editor's ironic note on the metaphorical language of the poem.

=== Chapter XV: Saltpetre and Salt Are To Be Found in All Subterranean Creatures
_The synthetic conclusion of the Nitre-Salt proof sequence (Chapters XI–XV)_

*The Graduated Descent:* "The more heaven approaches earth, the more earthy and corporeal it becomes; and the more earthy it becomes, the more it becomes fixed; the more fixed, the less it burns and shines and ignites. Thus, saltpetre, descended from heaven, is quite volatile and hidden in water. In putrefaction, however, it becomes manifest. The more earthy and fixed it becomes, the more it turns alkaline, and through that fixation it increasingly loses its explosive power (*Fulmen*)."

*Specification by Kingdom:* As Nitre descends and becomes fixed, it takes on different names and qualities in each kingdom:
- In the animal realm: its volatile form = the burning, stinking spirit; its fixed form = the alkaline ash.
- In the vegetable realm: its volatile form = the burning spirit of wine (alcohol); its fixed form = Sal Tartari (potash).
- In the mineral realm: its volatile form = sulphur, naphtha, petroleum (all combustible = nitrous); its fixed form = stone, ore, incombustible mineral.

*The Combustibility Proof:* "That sulphur and similar inflammable things are saltpetric, we have proven above by showing that all inflammations stem from saltpetre and its addition." Sulphur in the mineral kingdom = the maximum fixation of Nitre compatible with combustibility. Beyond that fixation, Nitre becomes the incombustible minerals (arsenic, marcasite, metal).

*The Axiom Confirmed:* *"Ex quo aliquid fit, in illud resolvitur, et per quod aliquid fit, per illum ipsum resolvitur"* — Into that out of which a thing was made, it will be dissolved; and by that which made a thing, it will again be dissolved. Since minerals dissolve in salty/nitrous solvents, they must be consubstantial with salt — otherwise they would not be conquered by it. When a mineral is dissolved in its salty Menstruum and the water drawn off to one-third, a vitriolic or aluminous salt crystallises. This salt is the mineral's prima materia.

*The Grand Summary of Chapters XI–XV:* "Minerals are born of fermented, putrefied salt and nitre turned acid, which dissolves earth into itself and thereby becomes vitriolic and sulphuric, but is subsequently increasingly fixed by degrees. And just as they are born of a spiritual nitre and an acidified salt, they are reconverted into their first essence by such acidified nitre." Confirmation: *Mercurius, Sulphur, and Sal* (the three Paracelsian principles) = nitre and salt in different degrees of fixation and specification. "That Sulphur and Mercury are born of saltpetre and salt is clear. The more earth absorbs a corrosive (Acidum), the more it becomes sulphuric. If it is rendered alkaline (gets into an alkaline spot that kills the corrosive), it turns into a Mercury or mercurial progeny."

*The Final Synthesis:* "Saltpetre and salt are the seed of the whole macrocosm and are volatile and fixed, depending on how they are applied. They both are father and mother, active and passive, the steel and magnet of each and all things. The visible Elements — Air, Water, and Earth — are the casing or the dwelling place of these two essences and the matrix out of which and by which they produce and give birth to everything."

- Of the volatile Nitre and Salt → an *animal* is born.
- Of the half-fixed and half-volatile Nitre and Salt → a *vegetable* is born.
- Of the fixed Nitre and Salt → a *mineral* is born.

=== Chapter XXII Continued: Practical Teaching on Finding the Medium When Stuck
_The most practically important section of Chapter XXII; largely confined to the chapter's middle pages (p.162–173) and absent from the main chapter summary above._

*The Core Problem — Spiritus Vini vs. Corrosive:* When Spiritus Vini (the most volatile) and any corrosive acid (the most fixed class of acids) are poured together directly, they refuse to mix: "They will stand one above the other like water and oil, whistle and sing together like adders and weasels." If forced, they require long circulation and the corrosive still will not readily accept the Spirit. *This is the most common failure in all laboratory work.*

*The Solution — Graduated Intermediaries, Step by Step:*
+ Distil Spiritus Vini together with all gross Phlegm to the consistency of honey.
+ Drive through a retort: a *sharp vinegar* (Acidum) comes over — already more fixed than the preceding Spiritus.
+ *Now* pour this vinegar upon the corrosive: watch their quick conjunction.
+ *Now* pour the Spiritus Vini upon the conjoined vinegar + corrosive: watch their lovely union.
The key recognition: *"Wine vinegar is an intermediate nature between the spirit of wine and the corrosive — which very few are yet reflecting upon. Neither have I read it, nor seen it, nor heard it anywhere."*

*Making Vinegar Quickly (the Eternal Ferment Rx):*
In fall, take unripe grapes with stalks, pound to juice, put into a glazed vessel, set in the sun until completely dry. Take the worst, sourest wine; distil off all its Spiritus Vini (preserve this). Pour the residual wine onto the dried grapes in a small oak or birch cask. Set in a warm spot. When it smells sour (a few days), run off through the bung; pour more distilled wine upon it. *"You may do this kind of pouring on and pouring off for ever, as long as you live, and you need no other new vineyards. They form a mother and become an eternal ferment, and soon turn the wine into vinegar."*

*Finding the Medium by Kingdom (the Practical Reference Rule):*
When work in any kingdom gets stuck, apply this hierarchy:
- *Animal kingdom stuck:* Look in the animal kingdom for its own medium. If specific animal is unavailable, use human urine or excrement (which "has hidden in its centre the power of all animals"). If still insufficient, return to universals (rain, dew, snow).
- *Plant kingdom stuck:* Use wine and its constituents ("in that all plant powers are contained"). If insufficient, resort to universals.
- *Mineral kingdom stuck:* Use alum (concentrates all white minerals) or vitriol (concentrates all red minerals/astra). If insufficient, use universals: rain water gives the Volatile; vitriol gives the Acidum; mineral salt gives the Alcali.

*The Inter-Kingdom Medium Rule:*
"Animals and minerals are extremely opposed to one another, but the plant kingdom is in between. If the animal kingdom is to become homogeneous with the mineral realm, it cannot easily be done except through the plant kingdom as its uniting principle. Nor should the mineral kingdom be made homogeneous with the animal kingdom without plants." *Rule: always use the plant kingdom as intermediary between animal and mineral — never combine them directly.*

*The Gold-Making-Potable Sequence (mineral → plant → animal):*
"If gold is turned into a mineral salt (vitriolic, aluminous, etc.) and this salt is dissolved by a plant vinegar (which is already homogeneous with plant nature), the plant Acidum takes up the gold's mineral acid and transforms it into a plant nature. This vegetabile must afterwards be transformed into an animale. Thus, the mineral kingdom becomes pleasant and homogeneous with the animal by means of appropriate intermediaries." Three steps: (1) ☉ dissolved in mineral Acidum → metallic salt; (2) metallic salt sweetened with plant Acidum → plant gold; (3) plant gold further sweetened with animal Volatile (urine, urinous spirit) → potable gold homogeneous with human nature.

=== Chapter XXII, Addendum 1: The Mercury of Life — Rx
_A process for the preparation of Paracelsus's Mercurius Vitae, appended at the end of Chapter XXII (p.175–177)._

#lab[
  *Rx for Mercury of Life (Mercurius Vitae):*
  Rx. ☿ dulcis (Calomel) — 1 oz + 2 scruples (approx. 33.7 g). ☿ viv. (common quicksilver) — 1 oz + 3 drams (approx. 42.8 g). Grind each separately to a powder; mix well together. Put into a well-lined wide-necked retort. Moisten with a suitable Spiritus or Acetum (Spirit of Wine or distilled vinegar). Distil through all four degrees of fire until everything has passed over. Finally, place burning coal on the retort to drive over the last.

  When everything has gone over and cooled: gradually pour on the strongest Spiritus or Acetum so that everything dissolves into a beautiful red, turning into a blood-red juice. Circulate this to a nice sweetness with sufficient *Spiritus Urinosus* (urinous spirit — see below), by frequently pouring on fresh Spiritus and drawing it off again. When sweet: drive everything over per se two or three times with a subtle degree of fire in sand, very gently and slowly in a wide recipient.

  *Dose:* 1, 2, 3, 6, 8, 10 drops in water or any other vehiculum. "This medicine passes through the entire structure of the body and dissolves all." — Paracelsus, *Archidoxes* and *Clavi*, Book 10.

  *Spiritus Urinosus (the Sweetening Spirit):*
  Rx. Spiritus Vini — 1 quart. Pour over 2 Lots (1 oz) of Sal Ammoniac + 2 Lots of Sal Tartari. Draw over just to the point of dryness. Ready.

  *Auripigment-Mercury Menstruum:*
  Rx. Orpiment (Auripigment) and ☿ dulcis in equal parts — 1 oz + 2 scruples each. Make each separately into a sublimate. Mix together rapidly. Place in a retort with a receiver. With half a quart of best Spiritus Vini, distil gently out of sand until all the ☿ dulcis has gone over. Strengthen with a quarter part of Spirit of Salt. Result: dissolves common ☉ into an oil and, when drawn off with Spiritus Vini, yields a high red and sweet-to-the-tongue substance.
]

=== Chapter XXII, Addendum 2: The Nine Antimony Preparations
_A complete pharmacopoeia of antimony medicines, appended by the Rosicrucian editors at the end of Chapter XXII (p.178–188). These represent the Rosicrucian Brotherhood's practical additions to Kirchweger's theoretical text, based on Basilius Valentinus' *Triumphal Chariot of Antimony* (with Theodor Kerkring's annotations, Nuremberg 1724)._

The editors introduce this section: *"Among the medicines that are made from antimony, there is none to surpass the Stone Ignis. Basilius Valentinus himself says it should be considered one of the seven wonders of the world, since not a single man before him had learned all about its virtues, powers, operation and effect."* The Brotherhood adds: *"In our circle of wisdom the powers of this superb creature have been known for several thousand years, already by the ancient Egyptians shortly after the Flood."*

#lab[
  *(a) Glass of Antimony — Method 1:*
  Rx. Antimony crude — 4 parts. Colcothar (red calcined iron vitriol, Caput Mortuum of vitriol) — 1 part. Let flow together in a crucible. Pour into a copper or brass basin, preheated and greased with suet. Result: a beautiful black-brown Glass (*Vitrum Antimonii*) in which the soul of iron is conjoined. If this Glass is melted with Borax, it becomes still more beautiful and fixed — melts like wax at a candle flame.

  *(a) Glass of Antimony — Method 2:*
  Rx. Antimony crude — 1 lb. Melt. Gradually add calcined corals, crab's eyes, grated or burnt hartshorn, quicklime, calamine, steatite, calcined tin, Sigillated Earth, bloodstone — of any one chosen, take ¼ lb. (4 Lots). Melt together → a special Glass of each. (Note: use only one additive per batch, not all together.)

  *(b) ASA — External Wound Balsam:*
  Rx. Antimony crude — 4 parts. Caput Mortuum of vitriol (or quicklime for external injuries) — 1 part. Mix; melt in a crucible until it flows like water → black-red Glass. Powder with 6× its weight of Sal Tartari or Potash. Melt again like water → pour out → yellowish mass. Powder; mix with common quicksilver — 4 parts. Cement very hot in crucible several times. Lixiviate with hot water. Filter. Boil down gently to a residue in an iron pan. Set in a humid cellar → a reddish Balsam, Liquor, or Oil.
  *Use:* 1 Lot (½ oz) + 10–12 Lots of plantain water (or celandine, pimpernel, etc.). Wash wounds, cancers, tumours, gangrene (dry or moist), fistulas several times daily with moistened cloth. If burning sensation: dilute with more of the plant water.

  *(c) PHALAJA — Internal Medicine — Method 1 (Digest):*
  Rx. Antimony (powdered) — 4 Lots. Tartar (Cream of Tartar) — 4 Lots. Spirit of Nitre — 4 Lots. Spirit of Salt — 4 Lots. Grind all to powder; mix. Put in an alembic. Pour on 1 quart of strong red wine vinegar. Stand 1 month in a warm place (not the sun), stoppered with paper; shake daily. Add 1 quart of strong brandy or lightly rectified Spiritus Vini. Stand another month in warm place (not sun). Filter. Ready.
  *Dose:* 6, 8, 10, 20, 30 drops in a convenient vehiculum.

  *(c) PHALAJA — Method 2 (Volatile, more powerful):*
  Rx. Antimony crude — 1 part. Common salt (fixo) — 6 parts. Melt together → cinnamon-coloured mass. Dissolve in good vinegar; filter. Distil to a residue (*aludel*). Re-dissolve with fresh vinegar for 3rd and 4th times, drawing off each time in Bain Marie to just dryness. Then proceed similarly with Spiritus Vini. Finally: distil to oiliness. Mix this oil with Sigillated Earth until quite dry. Distil per gradus in a retort in open fire → yellow or red oil / tincture. Further circulate with rectified Spiritus Vini to greatest sweetness; draw off Spiritus to oiliness. Result: the right medicine. *"These two preparations deserve careful consideration, because the Salts being the best Aperitiva and Incidentia are contained within them."*

  *(d) Red Flowers of Antimony:*
  Rx. Antimony crude — 2 parts. Flowers of Sulphur — 1 part. (Iron filings — 2 parts; antimony crude — 4 parts; Nitre — 6 parts — optional to accelerate.) Mix well; sublime once, twice, or four times → dark crimson flowers rise. Let these flow into a Liquor in a cellar on a glass plate. Turn into a tincture with Spiritus Urinosus.
  *Uses:* Purifying the blood; abscesses, ulcerations; internal obstructions of glands and nerves; catarrhs, cold feet, typhus, plague. "They no longer cause vomiting because their arsenic has been ameliorated by the flowers of sulphur."
  *Dose:* 2, 3, 6, 8, 10 grains in a convenient vehiculum.

  *(e) Vinegar of Antimony:*
  Rx. Antimony Hungarian — 4 lbs. Hungarian Vitriol — 8 lbs. (or: Sugar of Saturn/Lead acetate). Pound and mix; put in a lined retort with a receiver; set in sand for 24 hours. Drive at first and second degree. Let cool; pour back any liquid from receiver. Pour on 6 quarts of Spiritus Vini. Digest 1 month in warm room. Distil the vinegar very gently in Bain Marie. Rectify the distilled vinegar 2–3 times over the salts after prior digestion. Use as Basilius Valentinus teaches.

  *(f) Sulphur of Antimony (the Salt):*
  Rx. Antimony crude — 1 part. Potash — 4–6 parts. Grind together. Melt in a crucible to a clear consistency; pour into an iron pan → cinnamon-red mass. Grind to powder; boil in water in iron pan — the salt dissolves. Filter; precipitate with vinegar or any other acid → Sulphur of Antimony falls to the bottom. Sweeten with water until all saltiness gone. Dry.
  *Fixation:* Mix antimony crude + common salt in equal parts (4 Lots each); melt in crucible. Gradually add the antimony sulphur (3 Lots) to the melt. Let all flow together 2–3 Paternosters. Pour off. Lixiviate salts. Sweeten the sulphur at bottom with water until salt-free. Dry. Put in a retort; pour on twice its weight of Spirit of Salt; distil strongly until quite dry. Calcine well. *Result:* a PANACEA — "better than the common diaphoretic remedies."
  *Dose:* 6, 10, 15 grains with or without a specific remedy, in water, wine, or soup.

  *(g) Signet-Star (Star Regulus Purification):*
  Rx. Purified Regulus Martialis (antimony + iron, brought to greatest whiteness) — 1 part. Nitre — 3 parts. Sublime together with nitre. Mix the sublimate with 4 parts quicklime. Make a sublimate again. Calcine gently for 3 hours; cool. Boil in water; filter; gently coagulate into a salt using iron pan. Set in cellar → flows into a *vulnary balsam* for all injuries and burns. The dry powder (after boiling down the mass): sprinkle on wounds, corrosive injuries, open cancers. *"It is an excellent remedy for improving, subduing and drying all the acidity and corrosiveness of the injury."* Combine with ASA for optimal results.

  *(h) Malleable Tin-like Body from Antimony:*
  Rx. Regulus Antimonii — 1 part. Sugar of Saturn (Lead acetate) — 1 part. Common salt — equal parts (*q.p.*). Mix and grind together with half their weight of finely powdered soap. Work gently in a crucible until soap is burnt, then increase fire until melted clear; pour out. *Result: a malleable Corpus.* If not sufficiently malleable, melt again with soap until desired malleability achieved. Uses: as described by Kerkring in his *Commentary on the Triumphant Chariot*, p. 291.

  *(i) The Stone Ignis — Three Routes:*
  The Lapis Ignis is the highest preparation from antimony. Three production methods:

  *Route 1 — Basilius Valentinus method (abbreviated):* Detonate Antimony as per Basilius (saltpetre detonation). To 1 lb of detonated material, add 4 Lots antimony crude; grind well; melt until flows. Extract the tincture with distilled wine vinegar; circulate with the appropriate *Spiritus Martialis* (iron-salt spirit, see below). Congeal and fix.

  *Route 2 — Faster:* Pulverised crude antimony or antimony ore — 1 part; Potash — 6 parts. Grind all; melt to water-like flow; pour off; cool; powder; boil with water in iron pan; filter; precipitate the sulphur with acid; dry. Melt sulphur with 2–3 parts potash; separate sulphur again (repeat to obtain sufficient tincture). Draw its salt from the tincture. *Result: Panacea for children's stomach mucus and worms. Dose: 1, 3, 10 grains with sugar (induces gentle vomiting in children).*

  *Route 3 (fastest, the editors' preferred method):* 
  Prepare the Philosophic *Spiritus Martialis*: Dissolve clean washed steel filings in Aqua Fortis + distilled wine vinegar (mixed). When dissolved, gradually precipitate with Spiritus Vini until solution turns ruby red (stop before it turns green and loses colour). Filter; distil to pellicle; crystallise. Rx: 1 lb of these crystals + Spirit of Salt (¼ lb). Cohobate 24 hours. Distil through degrees out of sand → *a fine, noble, truly philosophic Spirit of Iron, sweet on the tongue.* This *Spiritus Martialis* is used to fix the antimony mercury into the Lapis Ignis. Take the Butyrum Antimonii (made with the tri = triple distilled); unite the antimony mercury with it as Basilius Valentinus prescribes; add the *Spiritus Martialis* crystals; coagulate through digestion and fixation in an alembic with head and receiver until it turns into a *beautiful liquid-wax stone.* "In this way one can delight one's mind much faster!"

  *Bonus preparation — Blood-Red Potable Gold:*
  Rx. Butyrum Antimonii + Lead nitrate (congealed with quicksilver and dissolved per deliquiem) — equal weights. Mix until dry with brick dust and coal dust. Distil in a retort in open fire → an acidic Liquor goes over (both medicine and menstruum that dissolves Aurum Fulminans). Draw off to dryness in Bain Marie; sweeten residuum with rectified Spiritus Vini → a *blood-red solution* = Potable Gold. A white sublimate also remains behind. "Out of this the salt is drawn with the mentioned Menstruum, united with its red tincture, and thus one has conjoined the red man with his white wife."
]

